def create_model():
    model = Sequential()
    #Input layer
    model.add(Dense(units =15 , kernel_initializer = 'uniform', activation = 'relu', input_dim = 29))
    #Second layer
    model.add(Dropout(0.5))
    model.add(Dense(units = 15, kernel_initializer = 'uniform', activation = 'relu'))
    #Output layer
    model.add(Dense(units = 1, kernel_initializer = 'uniform', activation = 'sigmoid'))
    # Compile Model
    model.compile(optimizer = 'RMSprop', loss = 'binary_crossentropy', metrics = ['accuracy'])
    return model;

    if clf_name == "Local Outlier Factor":
        y_pred = clf.fit_predict(X)
        scores_prediction = clf.negative_outlier_factor_
    elif clf_name == "Support Vector Machine":
        clf.fit(X)
        y_pred = clf.predict(X)
    else:    
        clf.fit(X)
        scores_prediction = clf.decision_function(X)

    #Reshape the prediction values to 0 for Valid transactions , 1 for Fraud transactions
    y_pred[y_pred == 1] = 0
    y_pred[y_pred == -1] = 1
    n_errors = (y_pred != Y).sum()
    # Run Classification Metrics
    print("{}: {}".format(clf_name,n_errors))

    clf_report = classification_report(Y,y_pred,output_dict=True)

Conclusion¶

In [ ]:
The give dataset is highly class imbalanced because the normal transactions are more compared to
the fraudulent transactions.
we have to perform sampling methods to make it balanced
We tried various undersampling and  oversampling methods.
Performed visualization on the features to derive insights from the data.
In order to have good data for model building, the data needs to be scaled.
Calculated the performance metrics for all the various alogithms/models used.
Supervised Learning Methods  dominates Unsupervised Learning Methods for a imbalance dataset problem.

from follwing scores it appears that XGBoost performs overall best amonst all.

Model                                   Accuracy    Precision   Recall      F1 Score
Naïve Bayes with overrsampling          0.973772    0.051414    0.816327    0.096735
LogisticRegression with oversampling    0.978723    0.066874    0.877551    0.124277
Random Forest                           0.999456    0.958904    0.714286    0.818713
XGBoost                                 0.999508    0.948718    0.755102    0.840909
Decision tree                           0.999175    0.774194    0.734694    0.753927


Ensemble Methods needs higher computing powers and crashed many times with memory errors.

We tried with threshold values of 2.5 and 3.5 and found that as we go up in thresold value the number of 
case concluded as falsey fradulant decreases but valid fraud cases decreases so threshold value of 2.5 looks mostly
ideal for our dataset.
